05185nam a22007095i 9780824865139DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20002000hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248651397 a10.1515/97808248651392doi  a(DE-B1597)484085  a(OCoLC)1024009676  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aD767.99 M53bP69 2001eb 7aHIS0270002bisacsh04a940.54/262211 aPoyer, Lin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Typhoon of War :bMicronesian Experiences of the Pacific War /cLin Poyer, Laurence Marshall Carucci, Suzanne Falgout. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2000] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (512 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tILLUSTRATIONS -- tISLAND NAMES -- tPREFACE -- tChapter 1. WAR IN THE JAPANESE MANDATED ISLANDS OF MICRONESIA An Introduction -- tChapter 2. BEFORE THE WAR Islander Life in the Japanese Mandate -- tChapter 3. THE FIRST PHASE OF WAR PREPARATIONS Springboards for Japanese Expansion -- tChapter 4. DEFENSIVE PREPARATIONS The Japanese Military Takes Charge -- tChapter 5 .THE SECOND ROAD TO TOKYO -- tChapter 6. LIFE ON THE BYPASSED ISLANDS -- tChapter 7. THE END OF WAR -- tChapter 8. INAUGURATING AMERICAN RULE -- tChapter 9. THE LEGACY OF WAR -- tAPPENDIX A. List of Participants in Oral History Interviews, 1990 –1991 -- tAPPENDIX B .Chronology of World War II in Micronesia (West Longitude Dates) -- tNOTES -- tREFERENCES CITED -- tINDEX -- tABOUT THE AUTHORS0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWorld War II was a watershed event for the people of the former Japanese colonies of Micronesia. The Japanese military build-up, the conflict itself, and the American occupation and control of the conquered islands brought rapid and dramatic changes to Micronesian life. Whether they spent the war in caves and bomb shelters, in sweet potato fields under armed Japanese guard, or in their own homes, Micronesians who survived those years recognize that their peoples underwent a major historical transformation. Like a typhoon, the war swept away a former life. The Typhoon of War combines archival research and oral history culled from more than three hundred Micronesian survivors to offer a comparative history of the war in Micronesia. It is the first book to develop Islander perspectives on a topic still dominated by military histories that all but ignore the effects of wartime operations on indigenous populations. The authors explore the significant cultural meanings of the war for Island peoples, for the events of the war are the foundation on which Micronesians have constructed their modern view of themselves, their societies, and the wider world. Their recollections of those tumultuous years contain a wealth of detail about wartime activities, local conditions, and social change, making this an invaluable reference for anyone interested in twentieth-century Micronesia. Photographs, maps, and a detailed chronology will help readers situate Micronesian experiences within the broader context of the Pacific War.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xCampaignszMicronesia (Federated States). 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xNaval operations, American. 7aHISTORY / Military / General.2bisacsh1 aCarucci, Laurence Marshall, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aFalgout, Suzanne, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082486513940uhttps://www